her\nclass of preferred stock and divi\ndends therefore were paid out of\nsurplus. Net was equal to $1.29\na share on the Class \u201cA\u201d stock,\nsix months requirements for which\nare $1.75 a share. On the com\nbined preferred shares, net was\nequal to 42 cents a share. In\nthe first half of last year, net was\nequal to 53 cents a share on the\ncommon stock after allowing for\npreferred dividends.\nTotal assets of the company\nas of June 30, 1930, amounted\nto $165,274,246, against $158,679,-\n883 on December 31, 1929. Cur\nrent assets were $79,393,337 com\npared with $90,809,150 on the\nearlier date. Current liabilities\non June 30, this year, were $36.-\n045.183, against $38,137,584 De\ncember 31. last. Marketable se\ncurities, carried at cost, amount\ned to $7,688,251, against sl,Bll,\n282. According to the statement,\nthe value of marketable securi\nties on December 31, and June\n30, was in excess of cost.\nNo plans are being contem\nplated, according to the report,\nfor the Issuing of any of the in\ncreased Class \u201cB\u201d preferred stock\nauthorized by the stockholders in\nMay. The report explains that\nin the period of acquiring the\nGeneral Electric and Westing\nhouse, properties, it was not pos\nsible to issue a report for the\nfirst quarter and that minor\nreadjustments may still be nec\nessary to cover unfinished details\nOnce Lowly Scrub,\nCow Sets a Record\nCHARKOV, Ukraine, Aug. 18\n(I.N.S.).\u2014A red scrub cow which\nthe Ukrainian milk trust bought\n\u2022five years ago from a peasant\nfor $75 for experimental pur\nposes is now producing 61k kilo\ngrams (135 pounds) of milk a\nday, a record for Russia.\nIn its report on the \u201cfirst real\nSocialistic cow\" in Soviet Russia,\nthe trust\u2019s experimental farm\nclaims that Mria. as the animal\nis called, produced 10,136 kilo\ngrams (22,300 pounds) of milk\nlast year, a record which will al\nmost certainly be exceeded this\nyear. The trust called upon all\ndairy farms in the country for\n\u201cSocialistic competition\u201d to at\ntempt to break this record.\nOIL STOCKS~\n(Furnished by W, B. Hlhby Co.)\nBid. Ask.\nHorne Scrymser 14 HO\nBuckeye Pipe Line 5414 55\nCheseboro Mfg. C 0... 147 165\nContinental Oil ...A 5 20\nCumberland Pipe Line SO 40\nEureka Pipe Line 35 41\nGalena Signal Oil com 4 4%\nHumble Oil S 5 90\nIlla. Pipe Line 310 320\nImperial OU Canada 1914 19%\nIndiana Pipe Line 31 33\nInternational Pete 18>4 18%\nNational Transit 18 1714\nN. Y. Transportation 14% 15\nNorthern Pipe Lines Hot 40\nOhio OU \u00ab2% 53%\nPenna Mex Fuel 21 24\nSolar Ref Co 12 14%\nSouthern Pipe Line 10 15\nSouth Penn Oil 35 36\nSoutheastern Pipe Line... 40 50\nStandard Oil of Indiana.... 49% 49%\nStandard Oil of Kentuky... 31% 32\nStandard Oil of Nebraska.. 47% 48%\nStandard Oil of Ohio 75 77\nStandard Oil nf Ohio pfd.. 17% 18%\nSwan A Fink 10\nVacuum Oil 83 33\nMONDAY, AUGUST 18, IMO\nBaltimore Produce\nApples\u2014Supplies moderate. Western\nMaryland. Pennsylvania and Virginia,\nbu. baskets. Summer Rambos, large,\n$1.5001.75; very large. *3; medium. *1\n01.25;\nhigh as $1.50; various other summer\nvarieties, 50c051.50. Nearby, H-bu.\n\u25a0hampers, various summer varieties, 25\n\u00a9soc.\nBeans\u2014Supplies light. Nearby. Round\nStringless, per bu., $3.600 4.\nBeets Supplies light. Nearby, per\nbunch. 4 \u00a9sc.\nBlackberries Supplies light. New\nJersey, best, 15010 c per qt.\nCabbage Supplies moderate. New\nTork. bulk, per ton. Round type, s4s\u00a9\n50; large else low as $35. Car-lot sale,\nbulk, per ton, $43. Virginia, 100-lb.\ncrates, small to very small, few sales,\n$1.7502.25. Nearby, bu. baskets. Round\ntype. $101.15.\nCantaloupes\u2014Receipts Eastern Shore\nMaryland boat and truck light; nearby\nlight. Supplies limited; demand mod\nerate; market about steady. Eastern\nShore Maryland, various varieties, stand\nard 455. $1.2501.76; jumbo 365. $1,750\n2.25; flats. 75c\u00ae51.25. Nearby. H-bu.\nhampers. $1.2561.35. Honey Dews:\nFive California arrived; 1